<span class="comment"><font color=#000000>You got a valid point. A a trick could be to focus on a problem, encounter many ideas (especially from other fields), and see if you could apply that idea to solve that problem. A problem that's hard for a technical person to solve could be trivial to someone who looks at it from a psychological point of view, and vice versa.<p>But the key is to always have a set of problems floating in your head. Having an idea, and seeing what problems that idea can solve is not as effective, as you often end up trying to force a square into a hole.</font></span><p><font size=1><font color=#f6f6ef>-----</font></font></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr><td><table border=0><tr><td><img src="http://ycombinator.com/images/s.gif" height=1 width=120></td><td valign=top><center><a id=up_3391806 href="vote?for=3391806&dir=up&whence=%2f%78%3f%66%6e%69%64%3d%6f%4c%72%32%61%65%43%68%42%37"><img src="http://ycombinator.com/images/grayarrow.gif" border=0 vspace=3 hspace=2></a><span id=down_3391806></span></center></td><td class="default"><div style="margin-top:2px; margin-bottom:-10px; "><span class="comhead"><a href="user?id=sidi">sidi</a> 40 days ago  | <a href="item?id=3391806">link</a></span></div><br>
